column1: Usually, it is not a best practice, to ascertain whether or not a file is malicious from a hash value alone. Indeed when Trend Micro analyzes a suspicious file, different factors are being looked at - including the file itself, as well as its behavior.
Since a file hash is only a fingerprint of sorts to help ascertain the integrity of a particular file, it alone is not enough to ascertain whether or not a file is malicious.

IOCs are mostly to be used to perform sweeping activities targeting devices/network segment that are suspected to be compromised. Those are indeed Indicators of Compromise and not all of those Indicators are malicious. Those might also be used to perform Threat Hunting activities.

Moreover there exists different hashes that can serve as IOCs and that different from file hashes themselves. Those include imphash, Richhash, Metahash, ... For those ones, it is expected that no assessment can be shared in regards to corresponding file coverage via legacy detection components (pattern files).
